                </tr>
            </tbody>
        </table>

        <p>That&rsquo;s a savings of <strong>$4,600 to $21,600 per year</strong>, depending on which tools you&rsquo;re currently using. And the savings compound &mdash; because you&rsquo;re also eliminating the staff hours spent maintaining connectors, rebuilding broken pipelines, and manually assembling reports.</p>

        <h2>Beyond Cost: Why Consolidation Matters</h2>

        <p>The cost savings are real, but the operational benefits of consolidation may matter even more. Here&rsquo;s what changes when your analytics stack is one platform instead of six.</p>

        <h3>One source of truth</h3>

        <p>When your executive director, your board chair, and your major gifts officer are all looking at different dashboards built by different tools pulling from different exports at different times, the numbers don&rsquo;t match. &ldquo;We raised $4.2 million&rdquo; in one report and &ldquo;$3.9 million&rdquo; in another. The discrepancy isn&rsquo;t usually a bug &mdash; it&rsquo;s a date range difference, a fund exclusion, or a data sync delay. But it erodes trust in your data, and once your board stops trusting the numbers, every conversation becomes an argument about methodology instead of strategy.</p>

